    <stitle>International&#174; MaxxForce&#8482; DT, 9 and 10 Engine Service Manual - Cylinder Head and Valve Train -
        Recondition - Reface Valves
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="reface" graphiccount="6">
        <title>Reface Valves</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Valve Face</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If valves are in good condition and within specifications, they may be refaced to specified
                        angles.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent engine damage, maintain minimum valve face margin across the entire valve face. An
                        insufficient valve face margin will not allow proper heat dissipation, causing that valve to
                        warp or break.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f3350013376" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg5/EG5368.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Grind valve face</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Make sure there is sufficient coolant in the valve grinding machine reservoir. Turn coolant
                        pump on before grinding.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dress the grinder cutting stone using the dressing stud attachment.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f3350013377" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figh08/H08042.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Valve face angles</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Intake margin</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Intake valve angle</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Exhaust margin</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Exhaust valve angle</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Intake valves and exhaust valves have different valve face margins.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install valve in grinder and set grinder to specified intake or exhaust
                    <hotlnk document="eges3351_339.xml" xrefid="t335001301">valve face angle</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="t335001301"/>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Turn on coolant and grinder.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Removal of too much material may reduce valve face margin below minimum specifications.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Grind valve face. Only remove the minimum amount of material necessary.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f3350013378" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figh08/H08005.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Valve face margin measurement</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure valve face margin at four locations with a
                    <hotlnk document="eges3351_341.xml" xrefid="t335001303">vernier caliper</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="t335001303"/>. If any measurements are less than minimum
                    <hotlnk document="eges3351_339.xml" xrefid="t335001301">Specification</hotlnk>
                    <xref refid="t335001301"/>, replace valve.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Reface Valve Stem Tip</title>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent engine damage, leave sufficient material on the tip of the valve stem so the valve
                        bridge does not contact the valve retainer keys or valve rotator during operation. Maintain a
                        minimum of 1.524 mm (0.060 in) gap between the valve bridge and valve spring retainer keys.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para id="s1322.2" count="1">Dress the cutting stone using the dressing stud attachment on the
                    grinder.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f3350013379" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg5/EG5367.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Valve stem grinding</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install valve in grinder so the tip of the valve stem is close to the grinding stone.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Briefly touch the tip of the valve stem to the grinding stone. Only remove the minimum
                    amount of material necessary.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Inspect Valve Face-to-seat Contact</title>
            <figure id="f3350013380" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figh08/H08006.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Apply marker paste to valve face</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para id="s1322.3" count="1">After refacing a valve, spread a thin film of marker paste (Prussian Blue&#8482;
                    or equivalent) on the valve face and insert the valve in the valve guide.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f3350013381" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figh08/H08007.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Turn valve on valve seat</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply pressure to the center of the valve head while turning valve 90 degrees on the
                    valve seat.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove valve from cylinder head. Inspect impression on valve seat and valve face. Marker
                    paste should appear around entire contact surface of valve seat and valve face.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Perform impression inspection several times to rule out any errors.</para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>If marker paste contact impression is good, continue to
                            <hotlnk document="eges3351_328.xml" xrefid="s1325">Inspect Valve Springs</hotlnk>
                            <xref refid="s1325"/>.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>If marker paste contact impression is not good, verify correct valve face angles and then
                            continue to
                            <hotlnk document="eges3351_326.xml" xrefid="s1323">Resurface Valve Seats</hotlnk>
                            <xref refid="s1323"/>.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
